  <h1>How do you start rolling your actions!!</h1>
  <p class="description">
    Sending event just takes a single line of code. Following are some of the code-snippets which can be used to get the events into rule bot.
    The example code uses common event names for description, though you can use any names for an event.
  </p>

  <!--  Page Load Event -->
  <h2> Sample event </h2>
  <p class="description">
    For example - you can track purchase of book by simply calling sendEvent api.
  </p>
  <div class="code_section">
    <pre class="prettyprint">
$("#purchase").click(function(){
    rb.track("book_purchase",{
        'book' : { 
                     'name' : 'alchemist',
                     'author': 'Paulo Coelho',
                     'isbn': 'ISBN 0-06-250217-4'
                 },
        'price': 3.2,
        'location': 'plano'
    });      
});
    </pre>
    <p class="description">
      This will trigger an asynchronous call to register an event "book_purchase" with rule bot. <br/><br/>
      This call eventually does some processing behind.<br/><br/>
      a). Events sent are accessible to set actions through dashboard.<br/><br/>
      b). Any actions already configured on this event will get executed.

      This way you can track any user interactions by using single function call. You can use any event name you desire.
    </p>

  </div>

  <h3> Following are some of the most useful function calls. </h3>


  <!--  Page Load Event -->
  <h2> Page Load Javascript </h2>
  <p class="description">
    Say you want to track users on page load and invoke actions. You can use a following function call to do the same.
  </p>
  <div class="code_section">
    <pre class="prettyprint">
rb.track("page_load",{
  'user' : {
      'name' : 'Lee Cooper',
      'gender' : 'male'    
  },
  'location' : 'Plano'
});      
    </pre>
    <p class="description">
    </p>

  </div>  
 
  <!--  Identify -->
  <h2> Identify Javascript </h2>
  <p class="description">
    You can use this function call to uniquely identify the user. The unique identifaction generated by this call is used to invoke actions when events are send.
    Ideally it is desired to identify the user before sending any event. 
  </p>
  <div class="code_section">
    <pre class="prettyprint">
rb.identify("213462356902");
    </pre>
  </div>    

  <!--  Set User Properties Event -->
  <h2> Set User Properties Javascript </h2>
  <p class="description">
    Use this function call to describe the user with properties. 
    Ideally it is desired to describe the user before sending any event so that actions can be invoked accordingly. 
  </p>
  <div class="code_section">
    <pre class="prettyprint">
rb.track("set_user",{
  'name' : 'John Doe',
  'gender': 38,
  'location' : {
      'city' : 'Palo Alto',
      'country': 'USA' 
  }
});      
    </pre>
  </div>    
